allocate_array_integer.description:
This function allocates a integer to the inputed array.
The new integer will be stored in the index slot in the
inputed integer array.

generate_integer_array.description:
This function generates an integer  array  out  of  the
inputed length. It cleans every slot in the array to be
the \0 character.

integer_array_length.description:
This function  calculates  the  length  of  an  integer
array. It does that with help of the \0 characters. The
first \0 character decides the length.

array_contains_integer.description:
This function checks if the array contains one or  more
of the integer. The function looks over the  array  and
returns positive if the integer was found.

delete_array_integer.description:
The function deletes a integer at slot index  from  the
inputed array, by moving the chosen integer to the  end
and then replace it with a \0 character.

add_array_integer.description:
The function  allocates  the  integer  to  the  inputed
array, by calling the  allocate_array_integer  function
with the length as the index.

sort_integer_array.description:
To sort the inputed array,  the  function  uses  bubble
sort. With  help  of  the  length  of  the  array,  the
function can sort relatively fast.

remove_array_integer.description:
This function removes  the  inputed  integer  from  the
array. The function calls  the  delete  function  after
calculating the index of the integer.

compare_integer_arrays.description:
This function compares the two arrays that comes in  as
parameters. It compares every integer after each other.
The arrays must be same length.

remove_array_integers.description:
This function removes  every  integer  in  the  inputed
array, bu using the  remove  function  it  removes  the
integer until there is no more in the array.

array_integer_amount.description:
The function returns the  amount  of  inputed  integers
there are in the array. This function can  be  used  to
find the frequency of the integer.

integers_range_between.description:
This function uses the  integer_range_between  function
to check if all the integers range between the  minimum
and the maximum integers.

generate_random_array.description:
To generate a random array, you will use this function.
With the help of a minimum and a  maximum  integer,  it
generates a array with length random integers.

reverse_integer_array.description:
This function reverses the order of the integers inside
the array. It creates a new array and fill it with  the
integers backwards.

add_array_integers.description:
This function uses the  add_array_integer  function  to
add amount integers  to  the  inputed  array.  This  is
useful when you need to add multiple integers.

integer_array_stdout.description:
This function prints out an array to the  console  with
standard output. This  is  helpful  when  you  want  to
debug, not for actual programs.

compare_array_content.description:
To compare two arrays without caring about the order of
the integers, you can use this function. It  sorts  the
arrays and then compare them.

duplicate_integer_array.description:
If you want to  have  two  copies  of  the  same  array
without messing with the  memory  allocation,  you  can
duplicate your array with this.

array_index_integer.description:
To get the integer that is in the  index  slot  of  the
array, you can use this function to don't  confuse  any
programmer that don't program in C.

shuffle_integer_array.description:
This function shuffles the integer array  pretty  well.
If you aren't happy of the results I recommend  calling
the function again.

generate_integer_vector.description:
This function generates a integer array with two slots,
both of the integers comes from the parameters.  Choose
which integers you want.

integer_array_total.description:
This function calculates the total  value  of  all  the
integers in the array added to each other. So  you  get
the sum of the arrays integers.

integer_array_section.description:
To get a section from the array, like cutting  a  cake.
You can use this function. The array  section  will  be
between the indexes you put in.

array_integer_index.description:
This function calculates the index of the first integer
that matches the integer you had as  argument  for  the
function in the array.

integers_inside_array.description:
This function checks if the inputed integers is part of
the inputed array. The order of the  integers  matters,
so it has to fit in the array.

generate_integer_matrix.description:
The function generates an empty matrix with the  height
and width that you put as arguments. Every slot will be
the \0 character.

allocate_matrix_integer.description:
To allocate a integer inside the  matrix  you  can  use
this  function.  It  is  like  a  backwards  coordinate
system, but with height and width.

integer_matrix_height.description:
To calculate the height of the  inputed  matrix  array,
you will have to use the total width of the  matrix  to
check if the arrays are full or not.

matrix_contains_integer.description:
This  function  checks  if  the  inputed   integer   is
somewhere in the inputed matrix. It checks all  of  the
arrays for the integer.

matrix_array_contains.description:
To check if a specific  array  of  the  inputed  matrix
contains the integer, you can  use  this  function.  It
checks only one array for a integer.

remove_matrix_integer.description:
This function removes the last of the  inputed  integer
that was added to the matrix. So you don't have to  say
on which height and width.

add_matrix_integer.description:
When you allocate a integer to a  matrix  you  have  to
give the function height and width,  here  the  function
adds the integer to the end of the matrix.

remove_matrix_array.description:
This function removes the last of the integer array  in
the matrix. Unlike the delete function, you don't need
to give the function a height and a width.

add_matrix_array.description:
This function lets you add  an  integer  array  to  the
matrix, without having to give it a height or a  width.
The array will be stored at the end of the matrix.

generate_random_matrix.description:
To generate a  matrix  with  random  generated  integer
arrays, you can use this function. The integers will be
between minimum and maximum.

integer_matrix_stdout.description:
This function prints out the inputted matrix  array  in
the console. Just like the other stdout  functions,  it
is not meant to look beautiful.

shuffle_matrix_arrays.description:
In this function, every array in  the  inputted  matrix
will be shuffled using the array shuffle function,  you
can always shuffle again if you want it better.

duplicate_integer_matrix.description:
If you want to of the same  matrix  without  having  to
deal with  memory  problems,  you  can  duplicate  your
matrix with this function.

remove_matrix_integers.description:
This function uses the  remove_array_integers  function
to remove  every  integer  that  matches  the  inputted
integer in the matrix array.

matrix_array_index.description:
If you want the  index  of  a  integer  array  in  your
matrix, you can use this function.  It  calculates  the
index of an array in a inputted matrix.

sort_matrix_arrays.description:
When you put in a matrix  in  this  function,  it  will
return  with  all  of  it's  arrays  sorted  using  the
sort_integer_array function on every array.

matrix_index_array.description:
This function returns the array that  is  in  the  slot
index inside the inputted matrix  array.  You  get  the
corresponding array for the specific index.

compare_matrix_content.description:
If you want to  compare  two  matrices  without  caring
about the order of them, you can use this function.  It
compares matrices after sorting them.

matrix_array_length.description:
If you want to calculate  the  length  of  one  of  the
arrays in a matrix, you  can  call  this  function.  It
returns the length of a index specific array.

compare_integer_matrix.description:
This function compares two matrices  using  the  height
and width of the inputed matrices.  They  must  be  the
 same height and width.

allocate_matrix_array.description:
When you want to allocate  a  matrix  array  with  this
function, it works the same way as allocate  a  integer
in an array. With help of an index.

delete_matrix_array.description:
This function deletes an array from the inputted matrix
using an index. It moves the array to the end and erase
it from memory, by making it empty

matrix_array_total.description:
The function lets you calculate the total value of  all
of the integers in one of the matrix arrays,  using  an
index to determine the array.

shuffle_integer_matrix.description:
If you want to shuffle around the arrays in  a  matrix,
you can call this function. It moves around the  arrays
 from the inputted matrix randomly.

reverse_integer_matrix.description:
This function generates  a  new  matrix  and  adds  the
arrays from the inputted matrix in backwards order. The
reversed matrix becomes mirrored.

reverse_matrix_arrays.description:
The function loops through the inputted matrix and uses
the reverse_integer_array function to mirror the  order
of the integers in every array.

sort_integer_matrix.description:
This function sorts the inputted  matrix  by  comparing
the arrays integers. The function does not compare  the
arrays by the total integer values.

matrix_array_integer.description:
This  function  returns  the  integer  of  a   specific
coordinate. By inputting the height and width that  you
want to access, you get the integer.

hashmap_keyword_exists.description:
This function loops through the  hashmap  and  compares
the current keyword to the inputted keyword, it  checks
if the keyword exists in the hashmap.

integer_hashmap_length.description:
To calculate the length of your hashmap,  you  can  use
this function. It checks if the current slot is  empty,
both the keyword and value are null.

hashmap_keyword_index.description:
This function returns the index of a keyword. It  loops
through the inputted hashmap and compares the keywords,
returns the index if it matches.

increase_hashmap_value.description:
If you want to increase the value of a keyword  in  the
hashmap, you could use this function.  If  the  keyword
does not exists, it will create it.

allocate_keyword_value.description:
This function let you allocate a value to a keyword  in
the  inputted  hashmap.  By  converting  the   inputted
keyword to an index, it allocates the value.

convert_array_hashmap.description:
When you have an array of integers and want to  convert
it to a hashmap, to see the amount of all the integers,
you can use this function.

convert_hashmap_array.description:
This function generates an array with the length of the
hashmap total value. Then it fills the array  with  the
integers from the inputted hashmap.

allocate_hashmap_keyword.description:
This function  lets  you  allocate  a  keyword  to  the
inputted matrix by using an index. You say which  index
you want to store the keyword, and it does that.

integer_hashmap_keywords.description:
Sometimes it can be useful to  have the  keywords  with
the same value. This function returns an array with all
the keywords that have a specific value.

delete_hashmap_keyword.description:
When you want to get rid of a slot in your hashmap, you
can call this function. It removes both the keyword and
value from the hashmap with an index.
